When dealing with a lot of async callbacks or promises we always run into the following pattern:

``` javascript
doSomeAsyncTask(function (err, res) {
  if (err) {
    // do something with error
  } else {
    // do something with result
  }
});
```

It's even more common when I want to wrap an async task within a promise:

``` javascript
new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
  doSomeAsyncTask(function (err, res) {
    if (err) {
      reject(err);
    }  else {
     resolve(res);
    }
  });
});
```

Because I do it really often in my code I came up with a very simple helper, which allows me to do this

``` javascript
new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
  doSomeAsyncTask(either(reject).or(resolve));
});
```

which I have found a very expressive and useful pattern. I am wondering if it's easily achievable with `lodash`. If not, then the question is whether it would be reasonable to add a similar feature to the library.

